    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "But isn't the \"rule of law\" supposed to respect the pluralism of a society? It feels like you're saying that for the state to be \"neutral,\" it actually has to be actively anti-religious by ignoring the fact that religion is a fundamental part of how huge portions of the population live. If a law is passed that specifically targets or contradicts a deeply held religious practice, hasn't the state already lost its neutrality and become oppressive? Why is the state's uniformity more important than the individual's right to conscience?",
